{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01Qc4VCpkkcHeJcHTyR93DgF","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Vector Similarity Search\n2\t\n3\tCore technique for finding semantically similar content using vector embeddings — the engine behind modern search, recommendations, and deduplication.\n4\t\n5\t## Key Points\n6\t\n7\t- Text is transformed into dense vector embeddings via transformer models (e.g. OpenAI, Cohere, sentence-transformers)\n8\t- Similarity measured with cosine similarity (angle between vectors) or dot product (magnitude-aware)\n9\t- Approximate Nearest Neighbor (ANN) algorithms trade small accuracy losses for large speed gains\n10\t  - **HNSW** (Hierarchical Navigable Small Worlds) — graph-based, best recall/speed trade-off\n11\t  - **IVF** (Inverted File Index) — cluster-based, efficient at massive scale\n12\t- Exact search is O(n) per query; ANN brings this closer to O(log n)\n13\t- Powers: RAG retrieval, recommendation engines, semantic search, duplicate detection\n14\t\n15\t## Related\n16\t\n17\t- [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md) — specialized stores that implement ANN indexing at scale\n18\t- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) — uses vector similarity as its retrieval step\n19\t- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — similarity search is applicable for deduplicating test cases and detecting redundant eval inputs\n20\t\n21\t## Sources\n22\t\n23\t- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n24\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b9ea5e4c-43e6-4437-bf16-7ac47bc8667e","uuid":"1fa3ca4d-00da-4d8b-a09c-1d5a371ec482","timestamp":"2026-07-09T15:40:37.895Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/vector-similarity-search.md","content":"# Vector Similarity Search\n\nCore technique for finding semantically similar content using vector embeddings — the engine behind modern search, recommendations, and deduplication.\n\n## Key Points\n\n- Text is transformed into dense vector embeddings via transformer models (e.g. OpenAI, Cohere, sentence-transformers)\n- Similarity measured with cosine similarity (angle between vectors) or dot product (magnitude-aware)\n- Approximate Nearest Neighbor (ANN) algorithms trade small accuracy losses for large speed gains\n  - **HNSW** (Hierarchical Navigable Small Worlds) — graph-based, best recall/speed trade-off\n  - **IVF** (Inverted File Index) — cluster-based, efficient at massive scale\n- Exact search is O(n) per query; ANN brings this closer to O(log n)\n- Powers: RAG retrieval, recommendation engines, semantic search, duplicate detection\n\n## Related\n\n- [Vector Databases](vector-databases.md) — specialized stores that implement ANN indexing at scale\n- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) — uses vector similarity as its retrieval step\n- [Agent Eval Harness](agent-eval-harness.md) — similarity search is applicable for deduplicating test cases and detecting redundant eval inputs\n\n## Sources\n\n- Ingested: 2026-07-09\n","numLines":24,"startLine":1,"totalLines":24}}}
